{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893725/1930051202/0233.xml":{"full_text":"Bnramswtle Herald\n__Eatabliahed July 4, 1892\nEntered u second-class matter in the Poetofflce,\nBrownsville, Texas.\n#Ht BROWNSVILLE HERALD PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nSubscription Rates\u2014Daily and Sunday (7 Issues)\nOne Year. 00\nSix Months... $4,50\nThree Months $2.25\nOne Month .75\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to the use\nfor publication of all news dispatches credited to It or\nnot otherwise credited in this paper, and also the\nlocal news published herein.\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas, Texas. 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City. Mo., 306 Coca-Cola Building.\nChicago. 111.. Association Building.\nNew York, 350 Madison Avenue.\n8t. Louis, 502 Star Building.\nLos Angeles. Cal., Room 1015 New Orpheum B!dg\u201e\n846 S. Broadway.\nSan Francisco. Cal., 318 Kohl Building.\nHARLINGEN OFFICE:\nCity News Co 114-A West Jackson Street.\nAmarillo\u2019s Rapid Growth\nAmarillo, away out In the upper Panhandle section\nof Texas, increased its population 178 per cent since\n1920. Figures released by the census supervisor of the\ndistrict showed a population for the city proper of 43,\n094 compared with 15 494 in 1920. Population of\ngreater Amarillo.\" according to the newspapers of\nthat city, is 43.878, but the official figure is 43.094.\nAmarillo owes a great deal of its growth to its res\nervoirs of natural gas. to its helium supply, to the de\nvelopment of the petroleum lakes on the fringe of\nPotter county, to the turning of virgin soil into wheat\nranches, to the rapid development of stock farms,\nand to the great cattle ranches which are found al\nmost in the foothills of the Rockies within the bound\nary lines of Texas.\nAmarillo has made a wonderful showing in ten\nyears. It has important daily newspapers. It has\nbig grain elevators. It has modern flour mills. It\nhas its skyscrapers which include 20th century ho\ntels. In the upper Panhandle and the northwest\nPanhandle section, in recent years, home seekers have\nbeen pouring in from other states, and Investors of\ncapital have honeycombed the so-called new country\nfrom the Okahoma border line to the El Paso ter\nritory for dividend-making fields.\nTexas, the Texas of today, is going a swift pace and\nshould be, if it isn't, the wonder of the American\nworld.\nMarrs Asks Another Term\nState Supt. S. M. N. Marrs has announced his cmv\ndldacv for re-election. He has held the office many\nterms. He is willing to serve the people another term.\nHigh court judges are elected and re-elected. Lieu\ntenant governors are given third terms. Railroad\ncommissioners are kept in office just as long as they\nretain the confidence of the voters. State comptrol\nlers are permitted to hold office as long as they can\n*et the voters to elect them. A land commissioner,\nwho has passed out of the picture, held the office for\ntwo decades. A close-up of the state shows county\nJudges and commissioners who never retire, and\ncounty clerks and collectors and sheriffs and prose\ncuting attorneys who never take a vacation. Sen\nators are elected two and three and four terms, and\nas for members of the house, they hold on forever.\nThen why all this bugaboo and ballyhoo about a third\nterm for a governor of Texas or any other common\nwealth?\nMoody's Campaign of Education\nA campaign of education is ever in order. Press\npublicity is the thing. Newspapers cover the com\nmonwealth. They are taken by the people who read\nand think. They are taken by those who read, but\nnot think, until the political fever begins to burn in\nthe veins cf the reader and then the reader is readv\nto pursue facts and figures and arguments placed in\ncold type by the linotype operator.\nGov. Moody has contributed a series of articles to\nthe press of the slate and his written matter has been\ngiven wide circulation. His farts have been taken\nfrom the official record. His figures have been taken\nfrom the official record. Presentment of the reforms\naccomplished in departments of government abound\nwith bristling points of interest to all the people, re\ngardless of political affiliation.\nNow the fairminded man who is seeking the truth\nwill find whole chunks of truth in the story of\nachievements of the administration of the young gov\nernor. the powerful forces which have been arrayed\nagainst most of the reforms proposed at all times\nfor reasons best known to the active \u2018ones are ell\nhoutted against the political sky, and the pressing\nneeds of Texas in a governmental sense are blazoned\nin large type In order that the uninformed or the mis\ninformed may thoroughly understand conditions as\nthey exist, economic or otherwise, under the skies\nof Texas.\nThose who spread the light of knowledge based\nupon the fundamentals of equal rights for all and\nhonesty in government are public benefactors and are\never entitled to an open-minded hearing of broad\nminded men and women when the forward move\nment of the commonwealth and the betterment of\nits people is the main object sought by a leader,\nwhether that leader be a statesman, an educator, a\nscientist, or whatnot.\nLooking Facts in the Face\nThe long-looked-for business revival may not be\ngin properly until fall, according to the Business Con\nditions Weekly issued by the Alexander Hamilton In\nstitute. Conditions are gradually Improving, and, as\nthe Weekly remarks.* *a foundation is being laid for\na sound business recovery\"; but the whole thing may\ntake longer than we have supposed.\nAll of this, of course, does not mean that we should\ngive way to pessimism and grow dour and hopeless as\nwe look to the future. It does, however, suggest that\nwe have been a little too optimistic for our own good\nThe problems that oppress American business can b\u00ab\nsolved, but they can only be solved if they are fully\nrecognized and carefully studied. A mere parroting\nof hopeful phrases Is not going to help us a bit.\n\u2018Embarrass\u2019 Them\nSo the Senate Lobby Committee has decided not\nto reveal the names of those congressmn who vote\ndry and drink wet!\nThe matter came up during the recent hearings\non prohibition. All of the dope was right at hand,\nready for publication. But the committee finally con\ncluded that to make this information public \"would\nonly cause embarrassment to a lot of people.\"\nYes. it would undoubtedly do that, all right. But\nisn't it just possible that these congressmen deserve\nto be embarrarsed? Is there any particular reason\nwhy anyone should be considerate the feelings of a\nman who votes for a law and then turns around and\nhelps to violate It?\nTextile Machinery for Marble\nFalls\nMarble Falls Is an ideal location for an industrial\ncenter. In the closing days of April 35 carloads of\nmachinery and equipment were put in the textile\nmill building there. All the raw materials await con\nsumption in Texas. Why not woolen mills, cotton\nmills, mohair mills, tanneries? Why not the road\nto wealth as shown by the census returns of the\nCarolinas, Virginia, Georgia. Tennessee and Alabama?\n-w\nI I\nThe Once Over\ni\nBy li- L PHILLIPS\nl----\u2014^\nUninformed Ulysses, who has been in a sort of coma\nfor the last year or more, was told of the recent mar\nket break and replied with some feeling. \u201cWell, that's\nwhat comes of electing A1 Smith president.\"\nCoffee, tobacco and autombiles are to blame for\nthe crime in this country, says Prof. Roland M. Har\nper of the University of Georgia. The only thing to\ndo would seem to be to return at once to cocoa, corn\nsilk and bicycles.\nSign suggestion for Indian restaurants; Not re\nsponsible for overcoats and Mahatmas.\nA former New\u2019 York alderman, whose sedan was\nfound loaded with rye and with a \"D. P. W.\" sign on\nit. says the car was stolen and that the thieves are\nresponsible for the tag and the liquor. Well, they\nshould be arrested and a stern example made of them\nfor forgetting to put aboard ice. glasses, lemons,\ncherries, lump sugar and free lunch.\nA broker was arrested in New York the other day\nfor riding a horse at a rate of 30 miles an hour. He\nwas probably trying to make it reach 100 and then\nmerge it wflh an airplane.\nWhen Admiral Byrd finally reaches America it\nmav be a question whether his lectures will come\nunder the heading of modem travel or ancint his\ntory\u2019.\n\nNocturne\nHush, my baby dolling!\u2014\nThe sandman's not here yet;\nThe dust upon you falling\nIs from mommer's cigarette.\nFrancis Mahon.\nOur Boarding House By Ahern\n\u00a5fjAPR-P-WMF^I VJAaA-T\nVoO \u201cto BE oO HaaIP -Tomoppou/\nL E'JEAilAlOi,ETA50Ai ,FoR -fME\nf PREMIER 5MovaIia!<3 A AlP\nPEMOAiS-fRA-flOAl OF mV\nREMARKABLE IaIa/EaStTi0*J f\nI VaJiLL E*HlBi\u201cT rf 5\n7 tWE MEK\u201cf ROOM AKlV S\njL A\"T A Giv/EM StOAiAO\n\u25a0t WolJ VaJILL PPAMi -TME PPAPE5\nBACK, PPESEAillAiCj A\n^PEC-r'ACLE. -TLfA-r UilU\nxg\\ BR\u00ab\u00abJQ FORTH A SALVJo\nn of Moi^AMs from\nI THE MEMBEP5 OF\nHim) -fM<s Moose Holdf\nif 5AV,MI5i>^ MA-S'aM \u2014LE-T\u2019s\nr PO l-r UMF PoVAL CLASS/\u2014*\nPRESS ME UP |Al A SCARLET\nv/ELUe-r' sui-r', uiif bio brass\npoor K'AioB BU-ffOAiS AM\u2019 ME\nVJEARIAl\u2019 OA!E OB JEM BLAckT\nbear HAt2s wMem\nL Vo\u2019 Give -1W\u2019 SIGNAL, AM\n\u25a0w BLOUiS A SILVER -TbaMPE-r,\n]\\_ -them PULL TH T pRAPES\nBACk, SdOLilAi*\nVou AAi\u2019VoUR\nlAlV/EAilToAA IAi\n^REGAL S-rVLE*\nI^e\nPREMIER\nSMou!i/a<3\n-TomoRRouJ\n0<mo wt ma w*v\u00bbat. me\n\nJrOIGHJrflAT\nA RADIO ^UROMANCE\n^ALMA SIOUX SCAR BERRY\n/futhorcf^M. FIT TIM* IMP. \u00bby cmtnl Prmt A^oditfoa. tee.\nCHAPTER 55\nElanda shivered in her lied cojd\nly. It seemed a thousand hours\nbefore she heard the key turn In\nthe lock and knew that Dtde and\nBang were coming home.\nShe turned over on her side and\nwaited\u2014cold horror seized her.\nCould she go through with it? She\nhad left her door open. She always\ndid when she was alone with the\nbaby so she could hear in c ase she\ncried.\nDixie and Bang ranv* ir. trying\nnot to make any noise. Dixie stop\nped at her door\u2014and she heard\nher whisper to Bang:\n\"Poor Andy is sound asleep.\nDead to the world.\u201d\nIt seemed no more than a sec\nond later that Dixie screamed. It\nwas such a blood-curdling scream\nthat the hair stood on Elanda\u20193\nhead. She got up hurriedly and\nrushed into the living room.\nDixie was standing in the bed\nroom door, her eyes wide with ter\nror.\n\u201cAndree! Where's Andree?\u201d\nBang's face was a blank.\n\"Isn't she in her bed? Maybe\u2014\nshe got up.\" He started for the\nkitchen.\nElanda sat down weakly.\n\"She\u2014she\u2014someone must have\nkidnaped her.\u201d\nAt that Dixie let out another\nscream. Bang took her by the\nshoulders. His voice was mild but\nhe was trembling and ghastly.\n\"Now, Dixie, don't lose your head,\nsweetheart. Wait. Maybe she is\nhere hiding some place.\"\nElanda wet her lips.\n\u201cShe\u2014she must be. I didn't hear\nanything. Oh. no one could have\ntaken her\u2014when I didn't know it.\u201d\nThen Dixie ran into her bedroom\n\"Oh, God! Htre are her paja\nmas.\u201d\nDixie covered her face with her\nhands\u2014and fell in a dead faint on\nthe floor. Bang seemed so dazed\nthat Elanda was afraid he. also,\nwould faint. He own legs were so\nweak and her heart quaking so\nthat she was almost helpless her\nself.\nBang picked up Dixie and laid\nI her on the bed. Elanda got some\n[water to bathe her face.\n\"We\u2014what are we going to do?\u201d\nBang turned to Elanda weakly.\n\"Call the police?\u201d\u2019\n\"Oh! No! No. don't call the po\nlice.\" Elanda turned white and\nclutched his arm. \"Wait\u2014Bang\nwait\u2014trust me. I\u2014I think I can\nfind her. Please wait.\u201d\n\u201cYou\u2014you must have some idea\nwhere she might be?\u201d He wiped\nhis head dazedly and sat down on\nthe edge of the bed. Elanda took\nthe cloth with which she had been\nwiping Dixie's head and put it on\ni his face.\n\"Wait.\" Bang trust me. Just\njust a few minutes. Go. lie down on\nthe couch\u2014and leave me with\nDixie a little while.\"\nElanda took his arm and led him\ninto the living room He was like\na little child letting her take care\nof him.\nShe knew she had to tell Bang\nsomething then. He would call the!\npolice\u2014and that would be fatal. So\nshe bent and whispered to him:\n\"I\u2014I sent her with Suwanee a\nlittle while. I was worried about\nDixie because she is going out too\nmuch. I\u2014I thought it would stop\nher.\"\nBang looked up at her with such\nblessed relief in his eyes that she\nwas happy she had toid him then.\nWeakly he rested on the couch, his 1\nhand- over his eye*. He laughed\u2014\nshakily.\n\"You\u2014you did it to scare her?\"\nElanda rushed back into the bed\nroom. Dixie was just coming to.\nElanda held the cloth on Dixie's\nforehead. In a moment Dixie open\ned her eyes. She tried to sit up but\nElanda pushed her back.\n'Rest a minute. Dixie. Bang is\ntrying to do something. He\u2019ll find\nher.\u201d\nMy baby, my poor baby,\u201d she\nwhispered hoarsely. \"Why would\nanyone want to take my poor little\ngirl?\u201d\nElanda was frightened but she\ndecided it was time to strike.\n\"Perhaps this is a punishment\nsent you for all the foolish things\nyou've been doing lately, Dixie!\nYou have not acted much as if you\ncared for your baby\nDixie looked up at her through\neyes that were suddenly full of\nquestioning.\n\"You\u2014you heard me talking with\nOreg yesterday\u2014didn\u2019t you?\u201d\n\"Yes. I know all about it. You\ndon\u2019t deserve a baby\n\u201cOh, don't say that, honey.\u201d Dixie\nclosed her eyes weakly. \"Don\u2019t talk\nthat way to me.\u201d\n\u2022\u2018Weil, you don't,\" Elanda said\nfirmly. \"You don\u2019t deserve a de\ncent husband, either. The way\nyou\u2019ve been neglecting the baby\nit's a wonder something hasn't\nhappened to her before this.\"\nDixie detected a something in\nElanda's mazier that caused her to\nraise up on her elbow and look at\nher again. Then she smiled feebly.\n\"You know where she is! If you\ndidn't you wouldn't be sitting here\nlecturing me like this. Oh. my\nGod, Elanda. how could you have\ndone this to me?\u201d\nElanda felt all her plans tumbl-!\ning.\n\"I don't know what you are talk\ning about,\" she began uncertainly. I\n\"Please get my baby!\" Dixie sat\nup then and shook her head from 1\nside to side weakly \"Don't\u2014you i\ndon't have to punish me any more\nI understand.\u201d\nElanda covered her face e\\\u2019i ha\nhands and burst out crying. In a\nsecond Dixie's arms were around\nher holding her dose. Dixie be\ngan to weep with Elanda.\n\"You don't understand, honey.\nPlease don't cry like this. Do you\nlove Greg Du Pont?\"\nT hate him. the rotter* For\nwhat he has done to you\u2014and Bang\nand the babv\n\"Elanda. look at me\" Dixie\nraised her head and there was a\nghost of her old grin trembling on\nher white face.\n\u201cI knew you heard that phone\ncall vesterday I intended you\nshould. I heard you come in. Can't\nyou understand I was doing it for\nyou? Bang knows all about it.\"\nBang appeared in the doorway.\n\"Where is the babv. Elanda\ndear?\"\nHe winked at Dixie\n\u201cSu\u2014Suwanee has her at his\napartment.\"\nDixie, suddenly her old self, let\nout a wild whoop of Joy. Elanda.\nsniffing, looked up at her as\nthough she thought Dixie had lost\nher mind.\n(TO BE CONTINUED\nFRUIT ClTP\nNothing is better to start a sum\nmer meal than filled grapefruit\nCut grapefruit evenly, remove all\npulp end juice and chill shells. Fill\nwith pieces of grapefruit from\nwhich all skin is removed, diced\nstrawberries, and fresh pineapple.\n-j\nI\n'Tbo<? MoffcES\u2019S1 UA?\nAN AUfULlTMt,-;\nCAUS't 'TaGHIOW'? ttAPL\nHE<? U\u00a3Ai?\nlfo\u00a3t 'fLlVPlG <3'WS'\n1MT <pAUGHTW? UOGL,,-*\n-Q^OPT yftMPC\nQhopt o^?r*r\nQ}Of?T AAU?\n\nI\nL\n---c,\nOut Our Way.By Williams T\n\\f vnhV,-KAA\u2014'THAT&\n7 H^ENr FONJ. VN1-W Ill/\nwauW home IWAAbt\n\\\u00b0F ^yk^ol ?CAM ^ETC ytiSlS\nVrrirrrTlI rwyv^/\nKS USNT Orr. Vn/kW MOTHERS C\\ET GrR*AV._r-ft 'Cnx?^\u20191**%t**cz)\u00bbc.\nNEW YORK\nVaudrvillr Performers Are Latest\nVictims of Night Club Gyp Art\nists\u2014They Got Good Jobs But\nWeren't Paid.\nNEW YORK, May 12\u2014Having\npracticed the not-too-gentle art of\ngyp upon patrons until they loet\npublic confidence, the more un\nscrupulous night clubs of Broad\nway have taken to gyping the per\nformer as well.\nWherefore, loud wails are to be\nheard in the glowing gulch.\nThe racket is, briefly, this: Vaud\nevillians have Deen having a par\nticularly tough season. Hundreds\nof them have been pounding the\nchairs of the agencies looking for\na \"break.\u201d A few shady agents\nmade a deal with a few shady night\nclubs. They would send the\u2019 work\nseeking performers to the night\nclubs, but under a very tricky ar\nrangement.\nThe actor would be told that there\nwas no way of knowing how well\nhis act would go in a cabaret. So\n\"audition nights\u201d were invented.\nThe vaudevillian would get an \u2018au\ndition\" with a chance for a job\nGrabbing at a passing straw, the\njobless ones naturally took the\nchance. Not even their carfare was\nadvanced\u2014yet they showed up and.\nwithout realizing that they were\nvictims of a sucker game, appeared\nas entertainers.\nFor which, of course, they re\nceived no pay, since this was merely\nan \"audition.\u2019\u2019 On subsequent\nnights other entertainers would thus\nbe gathered and \"return tryouts\u201d\nwould be arranged. So the night\nclubs got their talent and the agents\ngot a rakeoff from supplying the\nfree materia].\u201d\nConditions under which they had\nto appear have formed a particular\nground for complaint. Frequently\nmen and women found themselves\nin a single large dressing room, with\nonly a screen between them as they\nprepared for their numbers.\n\nA1 Crockett sends me one about\nCharles H. Sabin, the millionaire\nhead of the Guaranty Turn Com\npany.\nSabin had called at the St. Regis\nHotel to see a friend and, wtn\u2019.e\nwaiting at the room clerk's dealt.\nsuddenly pointed out two gents who\nwere walking across the lobby\n\u201cDo you know who those men\nare?\u2019\u2019 asked Sabin.\nThe clerk shook his head.\n\u201cWell, they're two of the biggest\ngunmen.\u201d\nThe clerk turned slightly pale,\nlooked around for aid and rang a\nsecret buzzer for the house detec\ntive.\nBut when the two men reached\nthe desk to register, they put down\nthe names of Captain James Pur\ndey and Thomas Purdey of London\nEngland.\nWhat Sabin had meant to state\nwas that they were two of the most\nfamous manufacturers of firearms\nin the world The House of Purdey\nhas been in the gun-making busi\nness for a century and a half, the\nbusiness having been handed down\nfrom father to son.\n\nSpeaking of vaudeville performers\nrr-^ ..-~~t\nHas Made Good\nwith\nMILLIONS t\nSame Price\nlor over 38 years\n25 meets lor 25^\nPure Economical\nEfficient\nMILLIONS OP POUNDS\nUSED BY OUB COVEBNMENT\nPPPTfVV\nLOANS\nOn improved city, residence and\nboslne** pro'\u00abrty.\nTodd Underwood\nComer Eleventh a'd Levee Sts..\nPhone 183 Brownsville\nKEYS MADE FOR EVERY\nLOCK\nWe Chance Combinations\nT. J. ROMMER\nRear of Miller Hotel\nPhone 722\nbeing out of work, reminds me that\nConey Island has been calling upon\nmany of them to do spieling for the\nfamous boardwalk sideshow attrac\ntions.\nThe tryout thus far showed them\nto be adrclt and unusually eloquent\nartists of the ballyhoo. They are\nwell acquainted with the \"ad lib\u201d\nwhich Is very necessary to this par\nticular racket.\na. tam\u00a5~\nBlue Printing and\nSupplies\nHarlingen. Texas\nThe Taste Tells The\nTale\nAnthony\u2019s Waffle\nShop\n517 12 St \u00a3hone\nThe Valley is\nProsperous\u2014\n....and in this organiz\ned bid for prosperity\nbank with ample re\nsources and the wide\nbusiness experience of\nthe First National Is\nplavtng an Important\npart This bank Is or\nganized completely to\nserve bnstnew. industri\nal and agricultural in\nterest* of the entire\nValler.\nFirst National Bank i\nEstablished in 1891\n3ROWNSVILLE, TEXAS\nTITLE INSURANCE\nWhen yon borrow money on real estate, many loan companies re\nquire the title to be Insured. The best test of whether a title is\nInsurable, is to have It insured. Require a title Insurance policy\nwhen yon boy.\nVALLEY ABSTRACT COMPANY\nPrompt Title Service\nBrownsville\nOpposite Court Boose\nPhone 1184\nEdinburg\nE. Hardman Odd.\nPhone 93\n_\n1911 1930\nSkelton Abstract Co.\nAbstracts of Title Title Insurance\nMerchants Bank Building Brownsville\nCARNEIRO, CHUMNEY COMPANY\nCertified Public Accountant*\nIncome Tax Service\nBROWNSVILLE SAN ANTONIO CORPU8 nHRISTi\nState National Ban i Smith-Young Towe Nixon Building\nI_______________\nDependable Phone 353 Prompt\nBROWNSVILLE TITLE COMPANY\nBROWNSVILLE. TEXAS\nAbstracts of Title Title Insurance\nWs cover til lands In Csm*r\u00abu CountyJ","height":"36556","width":"27432"}}
